      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure thing! The Maillard reaction is a chemical reaction between amino acids and reducing sugars that gives browned food its distinctive flavor. It happens when the temperature of the bread rises above 140-165°C (284-329°F). This reaction is responsible for the browning of your bread crust, as well as the delicious, complex flavors in things like seared steaks and toasted marshmallows. Keep an eye on the heat, and you'll see your bread turn from pale to golden brown, just like a well-tended campfire can turn a simple log into a majestic bonfire.",
