    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that makes sense. i also heard there's a difference between that and caramelization? like, are they the same thing or do they happen at different stages/temps?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're absolutely right, they are different but related processes. The Maillard reaction is a chemical reaction between amino acids and reducing sugars that occurs at a range of temperatures, typically above 140-165°C (284-329°F). It's responsible for the browning and flavor development in your bread crust and other foods.\n\nCaramelization, on the other hand, is the oxidation of sugar, a process used extensively in cooking for the resulting nutty flavor and brown color. It begins at around 160°C (320°F) and continues to higher temperatures. Caramelization occurs when sugars are heated without the presence of proteins, unlike the Maillard reaction, which requires both amino acids and reducing sugars. So, while both contribute to browning and flavor, they are distinct processes with different temperature ranges and requirements. Think of caramelization as the sugar's solo dance in the heat, while the Maillard reaction is a duet between sugar and protein.",
      "source": "target",
